rick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German, English, and French: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. In Britain, this Old French name, introduced by the Normans, reinforced the less common Old English cognate <i>Herebeorht</i>. The surname was taken to Ireland after the Anglo-Norman invasion and in the 16th century.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): from the German personal name (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Harbison","meanings":["Scottish (Glasgow): patronymic from the Older Scots and Middle English personal name   Herbert   (the change from <i>-er-</i> to <i>-ar-</i> was a common one in Old French and Middle English). An intrusive <i>n</i> later gave   Harbinson  ."]},{"name":"Hebard","meanings":["English (Surrey):","variant of   Herbert  , with assimilation of the first <i>r</i>. Compare   Hebb  .","variant of   Hibbert  ."]},{"name":"Harbert","meanings":["German and English: variant of   Herbert  ."]},{"name":"Herbers","meanings":["German and Dutch: patronymic from   Herbert  . It is found mainly in Lower Saxony and across the Dutch border."]},{"name":"Dickherber","meanings":["Probably a nickname for a fat person by the name of   Herbert  , of which <i>Herber</i> is a short form, or, more likely, in the north from <b>Die(c)kherber</b>, a topographic and distinguishing name for a <i>Herber</i> living by the dike, see   Dicke   2. Compare   Dickmeyer  ."]},{"name":"Hebert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Andre, Emile, Normand, Jacques, Marcel, Pierre, Lucien, Michel, Gaston, Alcide, Camille.","French (<b>Hébert</b>): assimilated form of   Herbert  . Compare   Abair  ,   Abar  ,   Abare  ,   Abear  ,   Aber  ,   Eber  , and   Ebert  .","German: variant of   Heber   1."]},{"name":"Herber","meanings":["German and Dutch: variant of   Herbert  ."]},{"name":"Herbertson","meanings":["Scottish (Glasgow): patronymic from the Older Scots and Middle English personal name   Herbert  ."]},{"name":"Hebb","meanings":["English (East Yorkshire and northeast Midlands): from the Middle English personal name <i>Hebb</i>, <i>Ebb</i>, pet forms of   Herbert  ."]},{"name":"Herb","meanings":["South German: nickname for a harsh or rough person, from Middle High German <i>herb</i> ‘tart, harsh’.","German: from the personal name <i>Herpo</i>, a pet form of   Herbert  ."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Joan Herbert was born about 1443, in Monmouth, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Walter Pembridge. She was buried in Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1443–":"umbes 1443–Surnud","1445–Male":"1445–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1474–1544":"1474–1544","1443–Female":"1443–Surnud","1544":"1544","1445":"1445","Abt 1443":"umbes 1443","1443":"1443","1474":"1474","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Raglan Castle, Monmouth, England":"Monmouth, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1443–":"noin 1443–Kuollut","1445–Male":"1445–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1474–1544":"1474–1544","1443–Female":"1443–Kuollut","1544":"1544","1445":"1445","Abt 1443":"noin 1443","1443":"1443","1474":"1474","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Raglan Castle, Monmouth, England":"Monmouth, Gloucestershire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"Abt 1443–":"environ 1443–Décédée","1445–Male":"1445–Décédé","–Male":"Décédé","1474–1544":"1474–1544","1443–Female":"1443–Décédée","1544":"1544","1445":"1445","Abt 1443":"environ 1443","1443":"1443","1474":"1474","Pembrokeshire, Wales":"Pembrokeshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Raglan Castle, Monmouth, England":"Monmouth, Gloucestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Joan Herbert est née environ 1443, à Monmouth, Gloucestershire, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils et 1 fille avec Walter Pembridge. Elleenterrée à Pembrokeshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni."},"de":{"Abt 1443–":"um 1443–Verstorben","1445–Male":"1445–Verstorben","–Male":"Verstorben","1474–1544":"1474–1544","1443–Female":"1443–Verstorben","1544":"1544","1445":"1445","Abt 1443":"um 1443"